\begin_layout Section*
Short Intro
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Plant distribution is driven by climate and internal dynamics between species.
 Climate fluctuations have and will continue to redistribute plants.
 These redistributions change the structure and function of ecosystems including
 the ability of plants to uptake carbon from the atmosphere.
 Above ground biomass typically serves as a proxy for ecosystem carbon storage
 potential.
 We use terrestrial ecosystem models based on theoretical understandings
 of plant redistribution to predict how carbon storage potential will change
 as climate changes.
 However, past biome shifts cannot be replicated by models.
 Specifically, it has been hypothesized that models do not adequately represent
 long term ecosystem stability and resilience.
 Without a better understanding of long term stability and resilience, we
 will not be able to predict above ground biomass shifts or the carbon storage
 potential of the terrestrial biosphere.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Paleoecological records have shown dramatic vegetation fluctuations in the
 Upper Midwest in response to changing climate over the Holocene.
 Such vegetation shifts have implications for the terrestrial carbon budget,
 but empirical reconstructions of the biomass consequences of vegetation
 shifts have not been previously developed.
 Here, we describe a new statistical model estimating changes in Midwestern
 biomass over the Holocene.
 We asked whether biomass was stable in the face of Holocene climate changes
 and whether this is truly ecosystem stability or simply the presence of
 a slow growing keystone species.
 There has been increasing evidence that climate-vegetation feedbacks make
 open forests unstable, and it has also been suggested that the stability
 of closed forests might be sensitive to changes in precipitation.
 Our statistical model estimates aboveground biomass based on fossil pollen
 data from 41 sites across the Upper Midwest.
 Biomass estimates in the model are calibrated against a Bayesian estimate
 of vegetation and biomass at time of settlement (~1850) derived from Public
 Land Survey data.
 Leave one out cross validation of our model reproduced the observed biomass
 with high precision (R^2 = .713).
 Predictions back through the Holocene occurred at sites with good radiocarbon
 control spanning vegetation types.
 We define ecosystem stability as the absolute change in biomass and calculate
 full posterior distributions of ecosystem stability based on 100 year estimates
 of aboveground biomass for the last 10,000 years.
\end_layout

