\begin_layout Section*
Description of Biomass over the Holocene
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Above ground biomass increased across ecosystems in the upper midwest during
 the holocene from 0 to 80 Mg/ha in 10000 BP to 20 to 120 Mg/ha in the present.
 The largest changes were in sites in mesic forests in northern Wisconsin
 and the Upper Peninsula of Michigan.
 These sites increased in biomass drastically either around 7000 BP or 4000
 BP.
 Lower biomass sites along the prairie forest boundary and savanna experienced
 decreases in biomass between 10000 and 8000 BP, little change in biomass
 from 8000 to 6000 BP, and increasing biomass from 6000 BP to present.
 
